d the industry's literature regarding strategies to expand markets for prescription drugs. He concluded that underlying the continual growth in medications, disease categories, costs, and insecurity is a relatively new perception of ourselves as inherently ill and in need of chronic treatment. This perception is based on clinical trials that we have largely outsourced to pharmaceutical companies. Those companies in turn see clinical trials as investments and measure the value of those investments by the size of the market and profits that they will create. They only ask questions for which the answer is more medicine. Drugs for Life challenges our understanding of health, risks, facts, and clinical trials, the very concepts used by pharmaceutical companies to grow markets to the point where almost no one can imagine a life without prescription drugs.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Okt 2020) 0aDrug utilizationxUnited StatesxElectronic books. 0aDrug utilizationzUnited States. 0aDrugsxSocial aspectsxUnited States. 0aDrugsxSocial aspectszUnited States. 0aPharmaceutical industryxSocial aspectsxUnited States. 0aPharmaceutical industryxSocial aspectszUnited States. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDUK Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311071183740uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780822393481zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780822393481423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780822393481.jpg  a978-3-11-071183-7  DUK Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_DUK_ALL  aEBA_DUK_EALL  aEBA_DUK_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles